# 17-VLANs (Part 2) – Notes

## Overview

This lesson continues VLAN fundamentals and introduces:

- trunk ports
- 802.1Q tagging
- trunk configuration
- router on a stick (ROAS)

The goal is to understand how multiple VLANs can share a single physical link.

---

## Access port vs trunk port

An access port:

- belongs to one VLAN only
- usually connects to end devices

A trunk port:

- carries traffic from multiple VLANs
- is usually used between switches or between a switch and a router

Access ports are untagged.  
Trunk ports use VLAN tagging.

---

## Why trunk ports are needed

If multiple VLANs exist across multiple switches, using one separate link per VLAN is inefficient.

Problems:

- wasted interfaces
- poor scalability
- routers may not have enough physical interfaces

A trunk solves this by carrying traffic from several VLANs over one interface.

---

## VLAN tagging

When traffic crosses a trunk link, the switch adds a VLAN tag to the frame.

This allows the receiving device to know which VLAN the frame belongs to.

Without tagging, the receiving switch would not know whether the frame belongs to VLAN 10, 20, 30, etc.

---

## 802.1Q

802.1Q, often called dot1q, is the VLAN tagging standard used for trunks.

Important points:

- it is the industry standard
- it inserts a 4-byte tag into the Ethernet frame
- it is used to identify the VLAN of the frame

ISL also exists, but it is old Cisco proprietary technology and is not important in practice for CCNA.

---

## 802.1Q tag fields

The 802.1Q tag contains:

### TPID
Tag Protocol Identifier

- 16 bits
- always set to `0x8100`
- identifies the frame as dot1q-tagged

### TCI
Tag Control Information

It contains:

- PCP
- DEI
- VID

### PCP
Priority Code Point

- 3 bits
- used for Class of Service

### DEI
Drop Eligible Indicator

- 1 bit
- indicates frames that can be dropped during congestion

### VID
VLAN ID

- 12 bits
- identifies the VLAN number

Because VID is 12 bits:

- total VLAN values = 4096
- usable VLAN range = 1 to 4094

---

## VLAN ranges

The VLAN range is divided into:

### Normal VLANs
1 to 1005

### Extended VLANs
1006 to 4094

Modern switches usually support the full range.

---

## Native VLAN

A trunk has a native VLAN.

By default:

- native VLAN = VLAN 1

Frames in the native VLAN are sent untagged over the trunk.

If a switch receives an untagged frame on a trunk, it assumes the frame belongs to the native VLAN.

This means:

- native VLAN must match on both ends of the trunk
- otherwise traffic problems can happen

This is called a native VLAN mismatch.

---

## Trunk configuration basics

Main command to configure a trunk:

```bash
switchport mode trunk
``` id="trunkcmd1"

On some Cisco switches, this may fail if encapsulation is still set to auto.

In that case, configure the encapsulation first:

```bash
switchport trunk encapsulation dot1q
switchport mode trunk
``` id="trunkcmd2"

On switches that support only dot1q, this extra encapsulation command is not necessary.

---

## Show trunk interfaces

Useful command:

```bash
show interfaces trunk
``` id="showtrunk"

This displays:

- trunk interfaces
- encapsulation type
- trunk status
- native VLAN
- allowed VLANs
- active VLANs on the switch

---

## Allowed VLANs on a trunk

By default, all VLANs are allowed on a trunk.

You can restrict VLANs for security and performance reasons.

### Allow specific VLANs

```bash
switchport trunk allowed vlan 10,20,30
``` id="allowvlan"

### Add VLANs

```bash
switchport trunk allowed vlan add 20
``` id="addvlan"

### Remove VLANs

```bash
switchport trunk allowed vlan remove 20
``` id="removevlan"

### Allow all VLANs

```bash
switchport trunk allowed vlan all
``` id="allvlan"

### Allow all except some VLANs

```bash
switchport trunk allowed vlan except 1-5,10
``` id="exceptvlan"

### Allow no VLANs

```bash
switchport trunk allowed vlan none
``` id="nonevlan"

Restricting allowed VLANs helps avoid unnecessary traffic on the trunk.

---

## Changing the native VLAN

Command:

```bash
switchport trunk native vlan 1001
``` id="nativevlan"

Best practice is often to change the native VLAN to an unused VLAN.

Important:

- native VLAN must match on both sides of the trunk

---

## show vlan brief

Useful command:

```bash
show vlan brief
``` id="showvlanbrief"

This command shows:

- VLAN IDs
- VLAN names
- access ports assigned to each VLAN

It does not show trunk ports as members of VLANs.

For trunks, use:

```bash
show interfaces trunk
``` id="showtrunk2"

