## Router on a stick (ROAS)

Router on a stick is a method of inter-VLAN routing using:

- one physical router interface
- one trunk link to the switch
- multiple router subinterfaces

Instead of using one physical router interface per VLAN, ROAS uses subinterfaces.

Example:

- G0/0.10 for VLAN 10
- G0/0.20 for VLAN 20
- G0/0.30 for VLAN 30

---

## ROAS configuration

First, enable the physical router interface:

```bash
interface g0/0
no shutdown
``` id="roas1"

Then create subinterfaces:

```bash
interface g0/0.10
encapsulation dot1q 10
ip address 192.168.1.62 255.255.255.192
``` id="roas2"

```bash
interface g0/0.20
encapsulation dot1q 20
ip address ...
``` id="roas3"

```bash
interface g0/0.30
encapsulation dot1q 30
ip address ...
``` id="roas4"

Important points:

- subinterface number should match VLAN number for clarity
- `encapsulation dot1q X` tells the router which VLAN belongs to that subinterface
- the switch side must already be configured as a trunk

---

## How ROAS works

When a frame arrives on the router:

- it arrives on the physical interface
- the VLAN tag tells the router which subinterface should process it

When the router sends a frame out:

- it tags the frame according to the subinterface configuration

This allows inter-VLAN routing over one physical link.

---

## Key concepts to remember

- Access ports carry one VLAN only
- Trunk ports carry multiple VLANs
- Trunk traffic uses 802.1Q tags
- The VID field identifies the VLAN
- The native VLAN is sent untagged
- Native VLAN must match on both sides
- `show interfaces trunk` is the main verification command
- ROAS allows inter-VLAN routing with one router interface and multiple subinterfaces

---

## Summary

Trunks are used to transport multiple VLANs over a single link.

802.1Q adds VLAN information to frames crossing trunk ports.

Switches do not route between VLANs.  
A router is still needed for inter-VLAN routing.

Router on a stick makes this routing more efficient by using subinterfaces instead of multiple physical router interfaces.
